investigating the aetiological trajectories of attention and social cognition in ASD</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E012930/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>At a time of growing interest in social neuroscience, the window into the interaction between brain and behaviour that is provided by the investigation of autism is becoming particularly significant. It is well documented that children with autism have difficulties in making inferences from social cues. There is growing interest internationally in the attentional responses that children with autism show to social stimuli.&amp;nbsp;It is timely to investigate how these responses develop and impact on the active use of social cues.&lt;br />&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Methods, such as eye-tracking, will be developed to enable exploration of the temporal and spatial processing differences in attentional development in ASD. Specifically, focus will be on response differences between those with and without autism when required to use cues in order to complete tasks successfully. This approach will examine whether attentional differences that underpin individuals with autism's difficulties in making inferences from cues by analysing the variation in attentional processes between participants who are able to successfully make inferences from cues and those that are not. Standardised observation scales, and the analysis of developmental trajectories, will be used to explore the interplay between aspects of autism and the information processing systems that may influence behaviours and symptoms.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>77763</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E012930/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Psychology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><